<LP>
   SEOUL -- South Korean corporate investment overseas surged
in the first quarter to $383 million on an approval basis,
the Bank of Korea said.
   The central bank said the tally involved 125 equity
projects.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Officials said South Korean companies have been
increasingly moving operations to low-wage countries in a bid
to boost export competitiveness weakened by increased wage
and other domestic production costs, while seeking better
market access to industrialized countries.
   By region, North America, mostly the U.S., attracted $164
million for 30 projects, almost 10 times the year-ago level.
